	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'll explain a bit differently: The first instruction that a 6502 CPU executes is <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">JMP &#40;$FFFC&#41;</tt>.<br /><br /><strong>[Mod edit: made use of {tt} around instruction/operand so the indirect addressing was more clear visually]</strong></div><br /><br />Technically it executes <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">BRK #$nn</tt> where the address register is loaded with <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$FFFC</tt> and all the writes are turned into reads. Same as all interrupt handlers (except the part about writes turning into reads), with their respective vector loaded into the address.

		

